ğŸ“„ Heartbeat Installation and Configuration Guide
ğŸ“˜ Overview
Heartbeat is a lightweight shipper designed to monitor the availability of services by pinging them at regular intervals and shipping the results to Elastic search. It's commonly used with the ELK Stack for uptime monitoring and alerting.
 
ğŸ”§ Prerequisites
â€¢	Elastic search and Kibana must be up and running.
â€¢	A Linux or Windows system to install Heartbeat.
â€¢	Internet access (for downloading packages).
â€¢	Sufficient privileges (sudo or admin access).
 
ğŸ› ï¸ Installation Steps
âœ… On Debian/Ubuntu:
wget https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/beats/heartbeat/heartbeat-8.12.0-amd64.deb
sudo dpkg -i heartbeat-8.12.0-amd64.deb
âœ… On RHEL/CentOS:
curl -L -O https://artifacts.elastic.co/downloads/beats/heartbeat/heartbeat-8.12.0-x86_64.rpm
sudo rpm -vi heartbeat-8.12.0-x86_64.rpm
âœ… On Windows:
1.	Download the ZIP from Elastic Downloads.
2.	Extract the ZIP file.
3.	Open PowerShell as Administrator and navigate to the extracted directory.
 
âš™ï¸ Configuration
ğŸ” Main config file: heartbeat.yml
Located at:
â€¢	Linux: /etc/heartbeat/heartbeat.yml
â€¢	Windows: <extracted-folder>\heartbeat.yml
ğŸ“ Sample Configuration


heartbeat.monitors:
- type: http
  id: my-web-check
  name: My Web Check
  schedule: '@every 10s'
  hosts: ["https://example.com"]
  check.response.status: 200

- type: tcp
  id: my-tcp-check
  name: My TCP Check
  schedule: '@every 30s'
  hosts: ["example.com:22"]

output.elasticsearch:
  hosts: ["http://localhost:9200"]

setup.kibana:
  host: "http://localhost:5601"
âœ… You can use type: icmp, tcp, or http depending on your use case.
 
ğŸš€ Start Heartbeat
On Linux:
sudo systemctl enable heartbeat
sudo systemctl start heartbeat
On Windows:
.\install-service-heartbeat.ps1
Start-Service heartbeat
 
ğŸ“Š Visualize in Kibana
1.	Navigate to Kibana â†’ Uptime.
2.	You should see your service checks listed.
3.	Use filters, search, and tags to monitor specific checks.
 
ğŸ”” Alerting (Optional)
To enable alerting:
1.	Go to Kibana â†’ Uptime â†’ Alerts.
2.	Create alert rules like "when monitor is down for more than X time".
 
ğŸ“Œ Tips
â€¢	Use heartbeat test config to verify config syntax.
â€¢	Use heartbeat test output to check connection to Elasticsearch.
â€¢	Use journalctl -u heartbeat or heartbeat -e for logs and troubleshooting.

